    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-01-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-01-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="3"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d3">
                <head>3. National Security Study Memorandum 8<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d3fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, Box 365, Subject Files, <gloss target="#t_NSSM1"
                            >NSSM</gloss>s, Nos. 1–42. Top Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-01-21">January 21, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <item>TO <list>
                            <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <item>SUBJECT <list>
                            <item>Technical Issues Concerning <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss>
                                Strategic Forces</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>In addition to the study of the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> military
                    posture requested in <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 3, the President has
                    directed the preparation of a separate study on technical issues concerning
                        <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> Strategic Forces including questions of
                    reliability and command and control.</p>
                <p>The President has directed that this study be performed jointly by the Department
                    of Defense and the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Staff in a manner to be
                    determined by the Secretary of Defense and the Assistant to the President for
                    National Security Affairs. The results of the study should be reported directly
                    to the President.<note n="2" xml:id="d3fn2">The study done in response to <gloss
                            target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 8 was incorporated into the response to
                            <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 3, the summary of which is printed
                        as <ref target="#d34">Document 34</ref>. See in particular section II, part
                        B, number 3, and section V. In his memoirs, <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> recalled his dissatisfaction with the response to
                            <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 8, a shortcoming he blamed on the
                        Pentagon. According to <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>, the
                        development of “strategies to meet contingencies other than all-out nuclear
                        challenge” remained incomplete until <persName corresp="#p_SJR1">James
                            Schlesinger</persName>’s tenure as Secretary of Defense from 1973 to
                        1975. (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>, <hi rend="italic"
                            >White House Years</hi>, pp. 216–217)</note>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
